{{other uses}} {{Redirect|Johnny Rebel|the American country singer|Johnny Rebel (singer)}} [[File:Unidentified young soldier in Confederate infantry uniform.jpg|right|thumb|200px|A Johnny Reb]] '''Johnny Reb''' or '''Johnny Rebel''' is the [[national personification]] of the [[Southern United States|Southern states]] of the [[United States]], or less generally, the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]] during the [[American Civil War]].<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/The-Life-Johnny-Reb-Confederacy/dp/0807104752#reader_0807104752 Bell Irvin Wiley. 1943. The Life of Johnny Reb: The Common Soldier of the Confederacy. LSU Press. 444 pages.]</ref> Patriots used Johnny Reb and his [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] counterpart [[Billy Yank]] to symbolize the common soldiers in the American Civil War of the 1860s.
Johnny Reb is usually pictured in gray wool uniform with the typical [[kepi]]-style [[forage cap]] made of wool [[broadcloth]] with a rounded, flat top, cotton lining, and leather visor. He is often shown with his weapons and with the [[Flags of the Confederate States of America#Confederate flag|Confederate flag]].
== Other uses ==
*"Johnny Reb" is a Confederate soldier's song written in 1959 by [[Merle Kilgore]] and popularized by [[Johnny Horton]].
